ructures. Right. It introduces this idea of a directed graph. Now, I know that sounds like something from, I don't know, an advanced computer science seminar. But it's actually incredibly intuitive once we break it down into its two basic parts. It really is. So, in the paper, a semantic system, which is just a broad term for any system of meaning from a physical library to the entirety of the internet itself, is described as a set of two fundamental things. Okay. What are they? First, there is a set of states. You can think of these as the nodes in a network. A state is the actual semantic content. It's a specific web page, a digital file, a book, a photograph, or even just a specific human memory. So, the state is the thing itself, the object. Exactly. And second, and this is where it gets interesting, there is a set of transformations. These are the edges in the network. A transformation is any valid action you can take to move from one state to another. Give me an example of a transformation. Sure. So, clicking a hyperlink is a transformation. Oh, okay. Querying a search index is a transformation. Looking up a citation in a bibliography, translating a text from French to English, or even just the mental act of recalling something from a previous conversation. Those are all transformations. So, information isn't just a giant bucket of isolated files sitting in a vacuum waiting for us. No, not at all. It is a network, right? A directed graph made of these nodes, the files or the states, and the edges, which are the literal paths we take to get from where we are to where the information is. That's spot on. Which brings us to the core distinction the author makes. And honestly, this is the pivot point for everything we are going to explore today. The difference between preservation and reachability. Right. So, preservation is simply the property that a state, a node, continues to exist over time. It's still on the server. Exactly. It means the file is intact. The da