ation overload, my initial reaction is that consolidating information is a good thing. Sure. It makes sense. I mean, I don't want to read 50 different disjointed, contradictory articles about the same historical event. I want one clean, consensus-driven page. If I'm researching the French Revolution, I want the definitive summary. Isn't this exactly what we want our encyclopedias to do? Sift through the noise and give us the signal. Yes. And for general navigability and rapid fact-checking, it is highly effective. It radically improves your ability to move from a state of ignorance toward canonical accepted content. But the paper provides a critical structural analysis of the unseen cost of this drive for consensus. It calls this process path compression with loss. Path compression with loss. Yes. When a smaller, more nuanced article is merged into a massive mainstream article, intermediate nodes in the graph are completely eliminated. Those intermediate nodes often represented prior framings, minority perspectives, regional understandings, or earlier states of consensus that were highly relevant at the time they were written. But I can hear people yelling at their audio players right now saying, wait, Wikipedia saves everything. I can go look at the edit history. Nothing is ever really deleted. You can, but this is exactly where the distinction between preservation and reachability becomes razor sharp. And why the graph model is so important. When that old article is merged, its prior existence is relegated solely to those internal edit histories. Okay, so it's buried. Buried. And here's the crucial technical reality that affects billions of users. Those edit histories are not indexed by external search engines. If a user arriving from Google or DuckDuckGo searches for a term that used to be a standalone article but is now just a merged paragraph in a larger page, they encounter the current consensus. There is no visible, intuitive indication that a rich, distinct 